00:01:39.700 --> 00:01:47.950
So temperature-- today's lecture
is largely about temperature.

00:01:47.950 --> 00:01:49.800
But we're going to
tie in all sorts

00:01:49.800 --> 00:01:51.870
of other things we've
learned over the course

00:01:51.870 --> 00:01:52.840
of the semester.

00:01:52.840 --> 00:01:53.760
So I'm very excited.

00:01:53.760 --> 00:01:59.170
Some of my very favorite
topics are coming back today.

00:01:59.170 --> 00:02:02.650
So effective temperature, we
talked about this a little bit

00:02:02.650 --> 00:02:05.170
when we were talking
about making bread,

00:02:05.170 --> 00:02:08.402
adding your baking
soda and about rates

00:02:08.402 --> 00:02:09.860
and why you put
things in the oven.

00:02:09.860 --> 00:02:13.840
And we talked about it has to
do with also the spontaneity,

00:02:13.840 --> 00:02:15.260
whether you change
the temperature

00:02:15.260 --> 00:02:17.610
and what your delta
H and delta S are.

00:02:17.610 --> 00:02:19.450
But we also talked
about rates and that

00:02:19.450 --> 00:02:21.850
increasing the temperature
often increases the rate.

00:02:21.850 --> 00:02:23.700
So many of us have
observed this.

00:02:23.700 --> 00:02:26.246
You increase the temperature,
you increase the rate.

00:02:26.246 --> 00:02:27.870
But today we're going
to talk about how

00:02:27.870 --> 00:02:33.570
you can quantitatively say
how much the rate might

00:02:33.570 --> 00:02:35.930
be changed-- the rate constant
might be changed if you

00:02:35.930 --> 00:02:37.810
increase the temperature.

00:02:37.810 --> 00:02:42.260
So in 1889, it was a
wonderful day for Arrhenius.

00:02:42.260 --> 00:02:46.130
He had been trying to
plot different values

00:02:46.130 --> 00:02:49.110
of rate constants
versus temperature

00:02:49.110 --> 00:02:50.710
to see what would happen.

00:02:50.710 --> 00:02:54.060
And then he tried natural
log of the rate constant k

00:02:54.060 --> 00:02:55.670
versus inverse temperature.

00:02:55.670 --> 00:02:57.150
And he got a straight line.

00:02:57.150 --> 00:02:59.850
And scientists always get
very excited when your data

00:02:59.850 --> 00:03:01.290
falls on a straight line.

00:03:01.290 --> 00:03:03.830
It means you figured
out some relationship

00:03:03.830 --> 00:03:06.230
between two values.

00:03:06.230 --> 00:03:09.020
So here is the Arrhenius plot.

00:03:09.020 --> 00:03:10.590
And we'll introduce some terms.

00:03:10.590 --> 00:03:14.560
So again, we're plotting the
natural log of k versus 1

00:03:14.560 --> 00:03:18.880
over temperature, 1 over
inverse kelvin over here.

00:03:18.880 --> 00:03:21.460
And here is our plot
of this straight line

00:03:21.460 --> 00:03:22.830
that Arrhenius found.

00:03:22.830 --> 00:03:28.510
Natural log of k on
the y-axis versus 1/T

00:03:28.510 --> 00:03:33.470
gives you a slope then of
minus the activation energy--

00:03:33.470 --> 00:03:37.615
so E to the little a is
activation energy-- over R,

00:03:37.615 --> 00:03:40.260
our good friend
the gas constant.

00:03:40.260 --> 00:03:43.320
And then the
y-intercept over here

00:03:43.320 --> 00:03:45.420
is the natural log
of something called

00:03:45.420 --> 00:03:49.160
A. We have a lot of different
A's in this particular unit

00:03:49.160 --> 00:03:50.090
of kinetics.

00:03:50.090 --> 00:03:52.260
This one is factor
A, sometimes called

00:03:52.260 --> 00:03:55.822
the Arrhenius factor,
A for Arrhenius.

00:03:55.822 --> 00:03:57.280
It has a couple of
different names.

00:03:57.280 --> 00:04:01.000
But importantly, it has the same
units as k, our rate constants.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:05.510
So what this plot told
Arrhenius back in 1889

00:04:05.510 --> 00:04:08.080
was that rate constants
vary exponentially

00:04:08.080 --> 00:04:10.380
with inverse temperature.

00:04:10.380 --> 00:04:12.210
So this was the first
kind of connection

00:04:12.210 --> 00:04:14.080
between rate constants
and temperature

00:04:14.080 --> 00:04:15.930
that could be used
to kind of come up

00:04:15.930 --> 00:04:18.640
with quantitative numbers.

00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:23.690
So factor A, this Arrhenius
factor, and the activation

00:04:23.690 --> 00:04:27.685
energy, E to the sub a, depend
on the reaction being studied.

00:04:27.685 --> 00:04:30.670
So they have to be measured
for the particular reaction.

00:04:30.670 --> 00:04:32.110
So it's a clicker competition.

00:04:32.110 --> 00:04:34.840
So we'll have a bunch of
clicker questions today.

00:04:34.840 --> 00:04:39.217
And why don't you tell me if you
think factor A is temperature

00:04:39.217 --> 00:04:39.716
dependent?

00:04:49.840 --> 00:04:50.340
All right.

00:04:50.340 --> 00:04:51.006
10 more seconds.

00:05:06.070 --> 00:05:07.090
Yep.

00:05:07.090 --> 00:05:10.250
The answer is no.

00:05:10.250 --> 00:05:14.860
And so what is this factor A?

00:05:14.860 --> 00:05:20.160
If we think about this in
terms of the plot, what it is

00:05:20.160 --> 00:05:26.910
is the rate constant
when 1/T is equal to 0.

00:05:26.910 --> 00:05:28.640
Because it is the y-intercept.

00:05:28.640 --> 00:05:34.982
And when 1/T is equal to 0,
what has to be true about T?

00:05:34.982 --> 00:05:36.320
Yeah.

00:05:36.320 --> 00:05:37.215
Infinitely large.

00:05:37.215 --> 00:05:42.500
So factor A is the
rate constant at

00:05:42.500 --> 00:05:46.330
an infinitely large temperature,
at a huge temperature.

00:05:46.330 --> 00:05:49.520
So it's the fastest that
particular reaction could ever

00:05:49.520 --> 00:05:52.800
go at this infinitely
huge temperature.

00:05:52.800 --> 00:05:54.275
So that's what factor A is.

00:05:54.275 --> 00:05:56.940
And of course, we
can't plug things in

00:05:56.940 --> 00:06:00.530
and say, how fast is this at
an infinitely huge temperature?

00:06:00.530 --> 00:06:03.820
So conveniently, you
can get that value out

00:06:03.820 --> 00:06:05.310
of plotting your data.

00:06:05.310 --> 00:06:08.930
You measure a bunch of rate
constants versus temperature.

00:06:08.930 --> 00:06:10.320
And you plot it
this way, and you

00:06:10.320 --> 00:06:14.210
can calculate this sort of
maximum rate constant possible

00:06:14.210 --> 00:06:16.790
for this reaction if
you had this infinitely

00:06:16.790 --> 00:06:19.460
huge temperature.

00:06:19.460 --> 00:06:22.245
What about activation energy?

00:06:22.245 --> 00:06:23.995
Do you think that's
temperature dependent?

00:06:38.790 --> 00:06:39.300
All right.

00:06:39.300 --> 00:06:40.195
10 more seconds.

00:06:55.200 --> 00:06:58.120
So no, it isn't.

00:06:58.120 --> 00:07:00.670
And so if we sort of just
think about it back here,

00:07:00.670 --> 00:07:02.600
the answer is no.

00:07:02.600 --> 00:07:04.780
Again, you plot
the rate constants

00:07:04.780 --> 00:07:08.720
over all these temperatures to
get one value out of the slope.

00:07:08.720 --> 00:07:12.830
So it is largely independent
of any kind of temperature.

00:07:12.830 --> 00:07:15.946
You get one activation energy
for the reaction in question.

00:07:15.946 --> 00:07:17.820
But it does depend on
the reaction, for sure.

00:07:17.820 --> 00:07:21.360
There isn't just one value
for this for everything.

00:07:21.360 --> 00:07:23.930
It depends on the materials.

00:07:23.930 --> 00:07:24.560
All right.

00:07:24.560 --> 00:07:27.090
So let's look at some
other ways that we can

00:07:27.090 --> 00:07:30.260
express the Arrhenius equation.

00:07:30.260 --> 00:07:33.170
So we have the
Arrhenius equation

00:07:33.170 --> 00:07:36.320
written as a straight line.

00:07:36.320 --> 00:07:41.350
And we can also do something
very, very simple to it,

00:07:41.350 --> 00:07:43.820
which is switch these two terms.

00:07:43.820 --> 00:07:46.330
And that gives us what
is officially known

00:07:46.330 --> 00:07:47.980
as the Arrhenius equation.

00:07:47.980 --> 00:07:51.040
So natural log of k
equals natural log

00:07:51.040 --> 00:07:53.750
of A, this Arrhenius
or factor A,

00:07:53.750 --> 00:07:57.350
minus the activation
energy over the gas

00:07:57.350 --> 00:07:59.280
constant times temperature.

00:07:59.280 --> 00:08:02.670
And of course, if you
want to solve for k,

00:08:02.670 --> 00:08:05.560
you take the inverse
log of both sides.

00:08:05.560 --> 00:08:09.830
And so then k is going to be
equal to this factor A-- again,

00:08:09.830 --> 00:08:14.200
measured for every reaction
in question-- e to the minus

00:08:14.200 --> 00:08:18.830
Ea, the activation
energy, over RT.

00:08:18.830 --> 00:08:20.410
So here is our equations.

00:08:20.410 --> 00:08:21.980
These will be on
equation sheets,

00:08:21.980 --> 00:08:23.580
so you don't have
to memorize them.

00:08:23.580 --> 00:08:26.430
But you already, if you've been
studying your equation sheet

00:08:26.430 --> 00:08:29.450
for exam four,
realize that there's

00:08:29.450 --> 00:08:32.409
a lot of symbols that are
very similar in these units.

00:08:32.409 --> 00:08:37.760
So we have a, in nuclear
chemistry, activity.

00:08:37.760 --> 00:08:41.474
So just keep in mind
what equation is what.

00:08:41.474 --> 00:08:44.059
When you're talking
about nuclear decay,

00:08:44.059 --> 00:08:46.300
you don't have your
activation energy term.

00:08:46.300 --> 00:08:48.600
So that should give
you somewhat of a clue.

00:08:48.600 --> 00:08:50.520
So one of the
challenges in the final

00:08:50.520 --> 00:08:54.590
is making sure you know
which equation is which.

00:08:54.590 --> 00:08:56.770
So let's look at an
example now where

00:08:56.770 --> 00:08:58.400
if we're given some
of the information,

00:08:58.400 --> 00:09:00.300
we can solve for other things.

00:09:00.300 --> 00:09:03.430
So an example, this is
classes at lunch time.

00:09:03.430 --> 00:09:08.360
So we can think about the
hydrolysis of an average lunch

00:09:08.360 --> 00:09:11.280
of sucrose to form a
molecule of glucose

00:09:11.280 --> 00:09:14.600
and a molecule of fructose as
part of the digestive process.

00:09:14.600 --> 00:09:16.810
So some of you might
have eaten already.

00:09:16.810 --> 00:09:19.730
You might be
digesting sucrose-- it

00:09:19.730 --> 00:09:23.230
comes in many different
forms-- right now.

00:09:23.230 --> 00:09:27.440
So using the information
about activation energy,

00:09:27.440 --> 00:09:29.620
we can predict what
the rate constant

00:09:29.620 --> 00:09:32.840
is going to be at a
different temperature.

00:09:32.840 --> 00:09:37.000
So some kind person measured
the activation energy

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:41.550
for this digestive process
at 108 kilojoules per mole

00:09:41.550 --> 00:09:46.730
and also figured out that
the k observed, observed

00:09:46.730 --> 00:09:53.165
rate constant, for this reaction
is 1.0 times 10 to the minus 3

00:09:53.165 --> 00:09:57.080
per mole or per at
normal body temperature.

00:09:57.080 --> 00:09:59.750
And so now we're asked
to calculate what

00:09:59.750 --> 00:10:04.050
that rate constant should
be at lower temperature, 35

00:10:04.050 --> 00:10:08.180
degrees Celsius, somewhat
below body temperature.

00:10:08.180 --> 00:10:09.540
So how are we going to do that?

00:10:09.540 --> 00:10:12.320
Well, let's remind ourselves
of our equations, our Arrhenius

00:10:12.320 --> 00:10:13.390
equation.

00:10:13.390 --> 00:10:15.570
So we know what Ea is.

00:10:15.570 --> 00:10:19.150
We were not told what our
Arrhenius factor A is.

00:10:19.150 --> 00:10:20.330
We don't know that.

00:10:20.330 --> 00:10:22.370
But we do know one
of the rate constants

00:10:22.370 --> 00:10:23.780
at one of the temperatures.

00:10:23.780 --> 00:10:27.662
So if we combine
these two equations,

00:10:27.662 --> 00:10:30.410
then we have an
appropriate number

00:10:30.410 --> 00:10:33.030
of variables to
solve for the rate

00:10:33.030 --> 00:10:35.490
constant at the new temperature.

00:10:35.490 --> 00:10:37.980
So let's combine
those two equations.

00:10:37.980 --> 00:10:42.780
So we have natural log
of k2, our rate constant,

00:10:42.780 --> 00:10:45.320
at temperature 2
minus the natural log

00:10:45.320 --> 00:10:47.310
of the rate constant
at temperature 1,

00:10:47.310 --> 00:10:51.230
which can also be expressed
as natural log rate constant 2

00:10:51.230 --> 00:10:53.080
over rate constant 1.

00:10:53.080 --> 00:10:58.010
And our natural log of the
Arrhenius factor drops out.

00:10:58.010 --> 00:11:01.310
And so we have minus Ea,
our activation energy,

00:11:01.310 --> 00:11:05.910
over our gas constant times 1
over the temperature minus 1

00:11:05.910 --> 00:11:07.760
over the first temperature.

00:11:07.760 --> 00:11:11.900
So we can put in our
values that we're given.

00:11:11.900 --> 00:11:15.900
So we have our first
rate constant down here,

00:11:15.900 --> 00:11:18.060
the rate constant at
the first temperature.

00:11:18.060 --> 00:11:19.910
We put in our
temperatures, making

00:11:19.910 --> 00:11:24.070
sure we convert them to kelvin
because our gas constant is

00:11:24.070 --> 00:11:25.410
in kelvin.

00:11:25.410 --> 00:11:29.470
And also, we are going to
convert our activation energy

00:11:29.470 --> 00:11:32.390
from kilojoules to
joules because we

00:11:32.390 --> 00:11:34.230
want to cancel our units.

00:11:34.230 --> 00:11:35.790
So now we can cancel joules.

00:11:35.790 --> 00:11:37.120
We can cancel moles.

00:11:37.120 --> 00:11:39.390
And we can cancel kelvin.

00:11:39.390 --> 00:11:43.360
And so that gives us
a new rate constant,

00:11:43.360 --> 00:11:48.740
7.6 times 10 to the minus
4 per mole or per second.

00:11:48.740 --> 00:11:53.550
And this is a lower rate
at a lower temperature.

00:11:53.550 --> 00:11:55.655
And in fact, that is often true.

00:11:55.655 --> 00:11:58.540
You have a lower rate
at a lower temperature.

00:11:58.540 --> 00:12:02.180
And this is one of the reasons
why it's a really good idea

00:12:02.180 --> 00:12:05.880
to keep your body temperature
at body temperature.

00:12:05.880 --> 00:12:09.400
And around this time of
year, people come in to MIT

00:12:09.400 --> 00:12:10.550
from warmer climates.

00:12:10.550 --> 00:12:13.250
And they do not have
appropriate clothing.

00:12:13.250 --> 00:12:17.110
And so your body does not
work well in the cold.

00:12:17.110 --> 00:12:18.350
The rates slow down.

00:12:18.350 --> 00:12:19.720
You're not digesting things.

00:12:19.720 --> 00:12:21.669
Your body is really
not doing anything

00:12:21.669 --> 00:12:23.210
at the rate it's
supposed to be doing

00:12:23.210 --> 00:12:25.260
these reactions
because they're nicely

00:12:25.260 --> 00:12:27.800
tuned to the appropriate
body temperature.

00:12:27.800 --> 00:12:32.070
So go out and buy a winter coat.

00:12:32.070 --> 00:12:37.400
So this now, this equation
that we just derived

00:12:37.400 --> 00:12:40.500
shows us the relationship
between rate constants

00:12:40.500 --> 00:12:42.030
and temperature.

00:12:42.030 --> 00:12:47.790
So again, natural log k2 over
k1 minus the activation energy

00:12:47.790 --> 00:12:51.710
over the gas constant
and our temperature term.

00:12:51.710 --> 00:12:53.310
And if we look at
this equation, we'll

00:12:53.310 --> 00:12:58.630
realize that if we have a very
large value for this activation

00:12:58.630 --> 00:13:01.850
energy, this Ea term
here, that's going

00:13:01.850 --> 00:13:04.000
to mean that the
rate constants are

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:05.850
very sensitive to temperature.

00:13:05.850 --> 00:13:08.320
If this is small, there
won't be a big difference

00:13:08.320 --> 00:13:10.090
between k1 and k2.

00:13:10.090 --> 00:13:13.190
But if the activation
energy is really big,

00:13:13.190 --> 00:13:16.490
there will be a big
difference between k1 and k2.

00:13:16.490 --> 00:13:19.810
The rate constants will be
very sensitive to temperature.

00:13:19.810 --> 00:13:20.310
All right.

00:13:20.310 --> 00:13:23.230
So now let's think about
rates and temperature.

00:13:23.230 --> 00:13:26.130
And let's think of
a cold temperature.

00:13:26.130 --> 00:13:29.900
Let's think, for example, of
liquid nitrogen temperatures.

00:13:29.900 --> 00:13:31.840
What do you think
happens to an enzyme?

00:13:31.840 --> 00:13:34.070
You have enzymes in
your digestive process

00:13:34.070 --> 00:13:36.940
that are hydrolyzing
sucrose that you

00:13:36.940 --> 00:13:38.370
might have had for lunch.

00:13:38.370 --> 00:13:39.900
What do you think
happens to enzymes

00:13:39.900 --> 00:13:41.858
if you put them at liquid
nitrogen temperature?

00:13:45.750 --> 00:13:47.820
They will slow way down.

00:13:47.820 --> 00:13:50.560
One would say they would
stop working entirely.

00:13:50.560 --> 00:13:56.180
They would just sort of
be, we call it frozen.

00:13:56.180 --> 00:14:00.020
And in fact, I use this all
the time in my research.

00:14:00.020 --> 00:14:03.990
So one thing we do, we study
the structures of proteins.

00:14:03.990 --> 00:14:07.170
And so we grow these
lovely protein crystals.

00:14:07.170 --> 00:14:10.020
And what we can do, we take
these-- a lot of times,

00:14:10.020 --> 00:14:12.580
the proteins or enzymes in
the crystals are active.

00:14:12.580 --> 00:14:15.140
They're able to convert
reactants to products.

00:14:15.140 --> 00:14:17.760
And so we can soak in reactants
and then take our crystals

00:14:17.760 --> 00:14:20.250
and dunk them in liquid
nitrogen and then

00:14:20.250 --> 00:14:21.740
determine the structure of that.

00:14:21.740 --> 00:14:23.670
And if we do it at
different time points,

00:14:23.670 --> 00:14:25.920
you can actually kind of
walk through the mechanism

00:14:25.920 --> 00:14:26.890
of the enzyme.

00:14:26.890 --> 00:14:29.480
Watch what happens at
various different states.

00:14:29.480 --> 00:14:31.850
So this is a very common
thing that's used.

00:14:31.850 --> 00:14:34.460
We like to do things
at liquid nitrogen

00:14:34.460 --> 00:14:37.640
to see things sort of--
we sort of pause it

00:14:37.640 --> 00:14:39.140
when it's dumped
in liquid nitrogen.

00:14:39.140 --> 00:14:40.240
It stops what it's doing.

00:14:40.240 --> 00:14:42.680
And we can capture
its structure.

