00:19:34.630 --> 00:19:38.400
Cold things are different
than warm things.

00:19:38.400 --> 00:19:40.330
Buy a winter coat.

00:19:40.330 --> 00:19:43.830
So everything slows
down in the cold,

00:19:43.830 --> 00:19:46.320
in terms of
elementary reactions.

00:19:46.320 --> 00:19:49.740
Our rate constants slow down.

00:19:49.740 --> 00:19:51.910
So now let's think
about a reaction

00:19:51.910 --> 00:19:54.180
and what's called a
reaction coordinate

00:19:54.180 --> 00:19:57.216
and consider what's
happening in a reaction.

00:19:57.216 --> 00:19:58.590
And then we're
going to come back

00:19:58.590 --> 00:20:00.750
to thinking about the
effect of temperature,

00:20:00.750 --> 00:20:02.601
where temperature really
makes a difference.

00:20:09.100 --> 00:20:11.790
We'll quiet down a little.

00:20:11.790 --> 00:20:15.870
So considering the reaction
coordinate, reaction coordinate

00:20:15.870 --> 00:20:19.190
the reactions of-- you bring
your reactants together

00:20:19.190 --> 00:20:20.620
and form your product.

00:20:20.620 --> 00:20:23.450
So two things coming together
to form something else,

00:20:23.450 --> 00:20:24.410
that is a reaction.

00:20:24.410 --> 00:20:26.140
And as you go along
in the reaction,

00:20:26.140 --> 00:20:27.716
that's your reaction coordinate.

00:20:27.716 --> 00:20:29.090
And we're going
to also introduce

00:20:29.090 --> 00:20:34.190
this term of activation
complex or transition state.

00:20:34.190 --> 00:20:37.020
So two molecules can collide.

00:20:37.020 --> 00:20:40.130
Two molecules
colliding, bimolecular.

00:20:40.130 --> 00:20:43.610
But every time those two
molecules come together,

00:20:43.610 --> 00:20:47.220
they're not necessarily
going to form a product.

00:20:47.220 --> 00:20:49.140
Why?

00:20:49.140 --> 00:20:54.570
So only when that
collision energy is greater

00:20:54.570 --> 00:20:58.570
than some critical energy--
which is sometimes called Emin,

00:20:58.570 --> 00:21:01.900
this sort of minimum energy
to get this reaction to go,

00:21:01.900 --> 00:21:05.580
or as I like to call it,
the activation energy, Ea,

00:21:05.580 --> 00:21:07.240
that's what we've
been talking about,

00:21:07.240 --> 00:21:11.560
our activation energy--
will you get a reaction.

00:21:11.560 --> 00:21:14.390
So you need to have
enough energy in your two

00:21:14.390 --> 00:21:16.310
things coming together.

00:21:16.310 --> 00:21:19.530
Those two things coming together
need to have a critical energy

00:21:19.530 --> 00:21:20.431
for them to react.

00:21:25.870 --> 00:21:28.990
So why is this true?

00:21:28.990 --> 00:21:30.900
You need to have
that critical energy.

00:21:30.900 --> 00:21:31.486
But why?

00:21:31.486 --> 00:21:34.420
Why is this necessary?

00:21:34.420 --> 00:21:39.010
So it's necessary because before
this reaction takes place,

00:21:39.010 --> 00:21:45.040
even if it's a very happy
reaction, things need to occur.

00:21:45.040 --> 00:21:50.290
So the two things coming
together need to often distort.

00:21:50.290 --> 00:21:52.170
Bonds might have to be broken.

00:21:52.170 --> 00:21:54.350
And new bonds need to be formed.

00:21:54.350 --> 00:21:58.030
And while that is occurring,
while there is distortion

00:21:58.030 --> 00:22:00.340
of the bond or
bonds are breaking,

00:22:00.340 --> 00:22:02.850
you need to have some
potential energy to do that.

00:22:02.850 --> 00:22:06.710
You need some energy to
make that reaction go.

00:22:06.710 --> 00:22:08.980
So the potential
energy of the system

00:22:08.980 --> 00:22:14.910
increases first while these
distortions are happening.

00:22:14.910 --> 00:22:17.620
So the encounter then
between them, you

00:22:17.620 --> 00:22:20.600
form some activated
complex, or what's

00:22:20.600 --> 00:22:23.430
known as a transition state.

00:22:23.430 --> 00:22:31.550
And that activated complex, it
can go on to form a molecule.

00:22:31.550 --> 00:22:35.690
Or from that activated
complex, the two molecules

00:22:35.690 --> 00:22:38.310
may just go apart again.

00:22:38.310 --> 00:22:39.910
So what determines
whether they're

00:22:39.910 --> 00:22:43.330
going to go on happily
to form their complex

00:22:43.330 --> 00:22:46.400
or going to depart
from each other,

00:22:46.400 --> 00:22:49.850
never to form a larger molecule?

00:22:49.850 --> 00:22:52.770
And the thing that
determines the fate

00:22:52.770 --> 00:22:54.810
is that critical energy.

00:22:54.810 --> 00:22:58.050
So only those molecules
with that sufficient energy

00:22:58.050 --> 00:23:02.000
to allow for those bond
distortions and rearrangements

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:03.820
will be able to go
on and make this.

00:23:03.820 --> 00:23:05.403
And you can think
about this, I think,

00:23:05.403 --> 00:23:07.770
in terms of a couple,
a relationship,

00:23:07.770 --> 00:23:10.380
that there's always some
work that has to go into it.

00:23:10.380 --> 00:23:11.310
It's never perfect.

00:23:11.310 --> 00:23:14.650
And if you put in this effort
and this work, you can go on.

00:23:14.650 --> 00:23:17.670
And if you don't really have
it in you and you're like, ah,

00:23:17.670 --> 00:23:18.850
you walk away.

00:23:18.850 --> 00:23:20.350
You don't have that
critical energy.

00:23:20.350 --> 00:23:23.790
You don't have that special
overcome, that activation

00:23:23.790 --> 00:23:25.284
energy, and you go back.

00:23:25.284 --> 00:23:27.450
So let's just take a look
at some molecules checking

00:23:27.450 --> 00:23:30.180
each other out and
figuring out if they have

00:23:30.180 --> 00:23:32.700
what it takes, if they
have that critical energy.

00:23:32.700 --> 00:23:34.330
Let's watch and
see what happens.

00:23:34.330 --> 00:23:35.280
Here they come.

00:23:35.280 --> 00:23:36.610
They're finding each other.

00:23:36.610 --> 00:23:37.890
They're circling each other.

00:23:37.890 --> 00:23:39.540
And oh my goodness.

00:23:39.540 --> 00:23:42.690
They had the critical
energy necessary.

00:23:42.690 --> 00:23:44.660
And they formed a
bigger yellow molecule.

00:23:44.660 --> 00:23:45.650
There they go.

00:23:45.650 --> 00:23:48.320
What a happy ending.

00:23:48.320 --> 00:23:53.260
So only those molecules that
have that critical energy

00:23:53.260 --> 00:23:56.030
can go on and form
their complex.

00:23:56.030 --> 00:24:00.380
And so here is where
temperature comes into play.

00:24:00.380 --> 00:24:04.920
Here is where temperature
becomes really important.

00:24:04.920 --> 00:24:08.450
Because they need to have
a certain amount of energy.

00:24:08.450 --> 00:24:12.160
And there's a relationship
between the kinetic energy

00:24:12.160 --> 00:24:15.330
of molecules and
their temperature.

00:24:15.330 --> 00:24:18.170
So let's take a look
at this plot over here.

00:24:18.170 --> 00:24:21.790
So this is, on one axis,
fraction of molecules.

00:24:21.790 --> 00:24:25.180
And on the other axis,
we have kinetic energy.

00:24:25.180 --> 00:24:28.340
So if you're at low
temperature over here,

00:24:28.340 --> 00:24:32.820
most of your molecules are going
to have a low kinetic energy.

00:24:32.820 --> 00:24:34.470
But it will tail off.

00:24:34.470 --> 00:24:38.140
And there will be some molecules
that will have a higher energy.

00:24:38.140 --> 00:24:41.240
And if this line here
represents that minimum energy,

00:24:41.240 --> 00:24:45.490
that critical energy or that
activation energy, in blue

00:24:45.490 --> 00:24:48.630
here we have those low
temperature molecules.

00:24:48.630 --> 00:24:50.700
Only a very small
fraction of those

00:24:50.700 --> 00:24:53.360
will have the energy to react,
will be able to overcome

00:24:53.360 --> 00:24:56.320
that minimum energy, that
critical energy needed.

00:24:56.320 --> 00:24:58.220
Now if you're at
high temperature,

00:24:58.220 --> 00:25:01.190
more molecules have a
higher kinetic energy.

00:25:01.190 --> 00:25:06.410
And if you see over here shaded
in orange, way more molecules

00:25:06.410 --> 00:25:08.960
have that critical
energy, have the energy

00:25:08.960 --> 00:25:14.060
necessary to distort those bonds
and go on to make a molecule.

00:25:14.060 --> 00:25:16.150
So here's where
temperature is important.

00:25:16.150 --> 00:25:19.112
So kinetic energy, pass it on.

00:25:22.390 --> 00:25:24.844
So let's draw some reaction
coordinates and think

00:25:24.844 --> 00:25:25.760
about what's going on.

00:25:25.760 --> 00:25:26.915
Yeah.

00:25:26.915 --> 00:25:28.740
AUDIENCE: For this
idea of collision,

00:25:28.740 --> 00:25:31.386
could it also apply to
the association reactions?

00:25:31.386 --> 00:25:33.362
Because that's
[INAUDIBLE] molecule.

00:25:33.362 --> 00:25:35.529
Or are [? they still into ?]
each other? [INAUDIBLE]

00:25:35.529 --> 00:25:36.528
CATHERINE DRENNAN: Yeah.

00:25:36.528 --> 00:25:38.680
So if you're talking
about the forward reaction

00:25:38.680 --> 00:25:40.285
and the backward
reaction of things,

00:25:40.285 --> 00:25:42.410
whether it's two molecules
that are coming together

00:25:42.410 --> 00:25:45.950
to form things or
molecules breaking apart,

00:25:45.950 --> 00:25:48.442
there's a critical
energy both directions.

00:25:48.442 --> 00:25:49.650
And we'll see that, actually.

00:25:49.650 --> 00:25:50.525
It's a good question.

00:25:50.525 --> 00:25:55.070
That kind of leads us in to our
reaction coordinate diagram.

00:25:55.070 --> 00:25:57.820
So most of this
is in your notes.

00:25:57.820 --> 00:25:59.820
There's a few
things that are not.

00:25:59.820 --> 00:26:03.060
But let's look at a
reaction coordinate diagram.

00:26:03.060 --> 00:26:08.470
And by that, I mean we have
Potential Energy, or PE,

00:26:08.470 --> 00:26:10.390
on one side.

00:26:10.390 --> 00:26:12.640
And on the other
axis, we have what's

00:26:12.640 --> 00:26:14.465
called just the
reaction coordinate.

00:26:21.220 --> 00:26:25.130
So if you're asked to draw a
reaction coordinate diagram

00:26:25.130 --> 00:26:28.740
on a problem set or an exam,
asking for potential energy

00:26:28.740 --> 00:26:31.370
versus reaction coordinate.

00:26:31.370 --> 00:26:35.640
Now our reactants are going
to have a particular amount

00:26:35.640 --> 00:26:37.770
of potential energy.

00:26:37.770 --> 00:26:39.520
And in this case, it's up here.

00:26:43.810 --> 00:26:48.820
And our products are going
to have some potential energy

00:26:48.820 --> 00:26:49.530
down here.

00:26:54.980 --> 00:27:01.750
And there will be a difference
in energy between these,

00:27:01.750 --> 00:27:06.590
our delta E. But these
reactants aren't just

00:27:06.590 --> 00:27:11.200
going to be able to go to
products without overcoming

00:27:11.200 --> 00:27:13.310
some kind of critical energy.

00:27:13.310 --> 00:27:19.490
So before they can go down
there, they need to go up here.

00:27:19.490 --> 00:27:21.790
So we have the
activation energy,

00:27:21.790 --> 00:27:25.840
f for forward direction.

00:27:25.840 --> 00:27:28.990
Also, if you're down
in products and you

00:27:28.990 --> 00:27:32.067
want to go back to reactants,
there's also a barrier

00:27:32.067 --> 00:27:33.150
that you have to overcome.

00:27:33.150 --> 00:27:35.550
And it's not just this.

00:27:35.550 --> 00:27:37.590
It's all the way up here.

00:27:41.170 --> 00:27:43.290
And so this would be
the activation energy

00:27:43.290 --> 00:27:45.660
of the reverse reaction.

00:27:45.660 --> 00:27:52.060
And this dashed line on the
top is our transition state

00:27:52.060 --> 00:27:54.160
or our activated complex.

00:27:54.160 --> 00:27:57.610
Both are two
expressions that are

00:27:57.610 --> 00:27:58.830
used kind of interchangeably.

00:28:02.390 --> 00:28:04.755
So this transition states,
some kind of weird mixture

00:28:04.755 --> 00:28:06.630
where they've come
together, and they're sort

00:28:06.630 --> 00:28:08.110
of breaking and distorting.

00:28:08.110 --> 00:28:10.170
It's not our final products.

00:28:10.170 --> 00:28:11.340
That's down here.

00:28:11.340 --> 00:28:14.870
But you need to go up in energy,
overcome an activation energy

00:28:14.870 --> 00:28:15.670
barrier.

00:28:15.670 --> 00:28:21.640
So the transition here, you need
to go up, and then you go down.

00:28:21.640 --> 00:28:27.410
So now let's think about
all of these energy terms.

00:28:27.410 --> 00:28:32.570
And what's true is that the
change in energy-- this change

00:28:32.570 --> 00:28:35.180
in energy between
reactants and products

00:28:35.180 --> 00:28:40.190
is equal to our activation
energy for our forward reaction

00:28:40.190 --> 00:28:47.010
minus the activation energy
of the reverse reaction.

00:28:47.010 --> 00:28:51.020
And this delta E over
here can be measured

00:28:51.020 --> 00:28:53.230
from a calorimetry experiment.

00:28:53.230 --> 00:28:54.955
And you might
recall back when we

00:28:54.955 --> 00:28:58.010
were talking about
thermodynamics that E

00:28:58.010 --> 00:29:01.380
is kind of closely
related to delta H.

00:29:01.380 --> 00:29:06.120
So we had this
equation at one point

00:29:06.120 --> 00:29:16.660
that delta H is equal to
delta E plus the change in PV.

00:29:16.660 --> 00:29:22.290
And we said that for gases,
there's about a 1% to 2%

00:29:22.290 --> 00:29:24.960
difference between
delta H and delta E.

00:29:24.960 --> 00:29:27.990
But for solids and liquids,
it's pretty much the same.

00:29:27.990 --> 00:29:30.380
So you can think
about this delta E

00:29:30.380 --> 00:29:35.210
like you were thinking about
delta H, for the most part.

00:29:35.210 --> 00:29:40.000
So now for this, if we
have some of the numbers--

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:43.180
if you know activation energy
in the forward and the reverse,

00:29:43.180 --> 00:29:44.720
you can calculate
delta E. If you

00:29:44.720 --> 00:29:47.370
know delta E and one of
the activation energies,

00:29:47.370 --> 00:29:49.220
you can calculate the other.

00:29:49.220 --> 00:29:52.810
So I'll tell you for
this particular reaction

