00:39:16.820 --> 00:39:17.570
But it's just fun.

00:39:17.570 --> 00:39:21.590
There's not many names for
equations in general chemistry.

00:39:21.590 --> 00:39:23.890
Look how similar
these equations are.

00:39:23.890 --> 00:39:25.920
These are very
similar equations.

00:39:25.920 --> 00:39:29.180
So we have the natural log
of rate constants here.

00:39:29.180 --> 00:39:32.230
Here we have the natural log
of equilibrium constants.

00:39:32.230 --> 00:39:35.060
Here we have our
activation energy.

00:39:35.060 --> 00:39:38.670
Here we have delta H.

00:39:38.670 --> 00:39:45.910
So if the reaction
is exothermic,

00:39:45.910 --> 00:39:48.800
if we increase the
temperature, what

00:39:48.800 --> 00:39:50.620
happens to our
equilibrium constant?

00:39:50.620 --> 00:39:51.842
Does it increase or decrease?

00:39:51.842 --> 00:39:54.940
You can just yell it out.

00:39:54.940 --> 00:39:57.740
It decreases.

00:39:57.740 --> 00:40:02.040
Now let's think about
what happens here.

00:40:02.040 --> 00:40:07.680
So our kobs now has an
elementary rate constant term,

00:40:07.680 --> 00:40:10.040
which is going to
increase with temperature.

00:40:10.040 --> 00:40:12.840
And it has an equilibrium
constant term,

00:40:12.840 --> 00:40:15.120
which is going to
decrease with temperature

00:40:15.120 --> 00:40:19.050
for an exothermic reaction.

00:40:19.050 --> 00:40:22.750
So we have these going
in opposite directions.

00:40:22.750 --> 00:40:27.500
So overall, we want to
think about the magnitude

00:40:27.500 --> 00:40:32.220
of our activation energy
term for our rate constants.

00:40:32.220 --> 00:40:35.930
And we want to think about the
magnitude of our delta H term

00:40:35.930 --> 00:40:39.880
in terms of the
equilibrium constants.

00:40:39.880 --> 00:40:45.140
So for the particular reaction
in question, you can look up.

00:40:45.140 --> 00:40:48.540
The activation energy
is a small number.

00:40:48.540 --> 00:40:51.570
And delta H, again,
it's exothermic.

00:40:51.570 --> 00:40:54.070
And it's a big number.

00:40:54.070 --> 00:40:55.690
So then if you're
thinking about that,

00:40:55.690 --> 00:40:59.640
if Ea is small and positive--
Ea is always positive.

00:40:59.640 --> 00:41:03.980
There is always a
barrier, always positive.

00:41:03.980 --> 00:41:08.440
Then the rate constant is only
going to increase a little bit.

00:41:08.440 --> 00:41:10.590
But delta H is a
big negative number,

00:41:10.590 --> 00:41:14.090
so the equilibrium constant
is going to decrease a lot.

00:41:14.090 --> 00:41:17.600
So for this particular reaction,
increasing the temperature

00:41:17.600 --> 00:41:20.370
actually decreases the kobs.

00:41:20.370 --> 00:41:23.670
And so for any
reaction, it depends

00:41:23.670 --> 00:41:27.430
on the magnitude of
Ea and the magnitude

00:41:27.430 --> 00:41:33.070
and the sign of delta
H. So again, large Ea

00:41:33.070 --> 00:41:35.600
means very sensitive
to temperature.

00:41:35.600 --> 00:41:39.700
Large delta H means that
the equilibrium constant is

00:41:39.700 --> 00:41:42.930
very sensitive to temperature.

00:41:42.930 --> 00:41:45.860
For an elementary
rate constant, it's

00:41:45.860 --> 00:41:49.430
always going to increase
with temperature.

00:41:49.430 --> 00:41:51.460
Because Ea is always positive.

00:41:51.460 --> 00:41:54.110
There is always a
barrier to overcome.

00:41:54.110 --> 00:41:58.170
Temperature always
increases a rate constant.

00:41:58.170 --> 00:42:00.400
But for an equilibrium
constant, it

00:42:00.400 --> 00:42:05.060
can increase or decrease because
delta H isn't always positive.

00:42:05.060 --> 00:42:06.720
Like the activation
energy barrier,

00:42:06.720 --> 00:42:09.990
it can be positive or negative.

00:42:09.990 --> 00:42:14.570
So the magnitude of delta
H, how big a number it is,

00:42:14.570 --> 00:42:16.630
tells you about the
magnitude of the change,

00:42:16.630 --> 00:42:20.080
how much the equilibrium
constant will change.

00:42:20.080 --> 00:42:22.630
Will k1 and k2 be
almost like each other

00:42:22.630 --> 00:42:25.440
or really, really different from
each other, those equilibrium

00:42:25.440 --> 00:42:26.440
constants?

00:42:26.440 --> 00:42:29.550
And the sign of delta H, whether
it's positive or negative,

00:42:29.550 --> 00:42:31.400
tells you the direction
of the change.

00:42:31.400 --> 00:42:34.920
Will it increase or decrease?

