00:45:24.100 --> 00:45:26.610
So rate constants
always increase

00:45:26.610 --> 00:45:27.835
with increase of temperature.

00:45:27.835 --> 00:45:30.450
That's our little k's.

00:45:30.450 --> 00:45:33.250
Because there is always
some activation energy

00:45:33.250 --> 00:45:34.980
barrier to overcome.

00:45:34.980 --> 00:45:37.380
There is always a
positive barrier.

00:45:37.380 --> 00:45:41.100
Whereas, for equilibrium
constants, K,

00:45:41.100 --> 00:45:44.450
you can have a reaction that's
exothermic or endothermic.

00:45:44.450 --> 00:45:45.900
And so that will change.

00:45:45.900 --> 00:45:49.730
It either increases or
decreases because delta H

00:45:49.730 --> 00:45:51.260
can be positive or negative.

00:45:51.260 --> 00:45:53.930
But activation energy
barriers are always positive.

00:45:53.930 --> 00:45:56.260
There's always a barrier.

00:45:56.260 --> 00:45:59.280
Always a barrier to doing
anything that's important.

00:45:59.280 --> 00:46:01.620
I've got to calm down.

00:46:01.620 --> 00:46:08.900
Le Chatelier tells me that
when a stress is applied

00:46:08.900 --> 00:46:12.760
to the system, I should
respond in such a way

00:46:12.760 --> 00:46:15.120
to minimize the stress.

00:46:15.120 --> 00:46:20.120
It's a very calming
rule in chemistry.

00:46:20.120 --> 00:46:22.680
Reactions don't like stress.

00:46:22.680 --> 00:46:26.140
And they'll respond in
a way to minimize it.

00:46:26.140 --> 00:46:31.320
So we've been talking
about Le Chatelier

00:46:31.320 --> 00:46:34.910
for a lot of the semester.

00:46:34.910 --> 00:46:37.580
And we've talked about
the effect of temperature

00:46:37.580 --> 00:46:40.610
on reactions previously.

00:46:40.610 --> 00:46:45.140
So if you add heat
to a reaction,

00:46:45.140 --> 00:46:47.990
it will want to respond in
such a way to minimize the heat

00:46:47.990 --> 00:46:49.780
or absorb the heat.

00:46:49.780 --> 00:46:53.222
So it shifts in the
endothermic direction.

00:46:53.222 --> 00:46:54.680
So we've already
talked about this.

00:46:54.680 --> 00:46:56.780
And nothing is new here today.

00:46:56.780 --> 00:46:59.640
But today, I'm going to
give you a different way

00:46:59.640 --> 00:47:03.120
to rationalize why that happens.

00:47:03.120 --> 00:47:04.971
So we're not changing
what happens.

00:47:04.971 --> 00:47:06.720
We're just going to
come up with a new way

00:47:06.720 --> 00:47:09.340
to rationalize the why.

00:47:09.340 --> 00:47:13.930
So we ended last time
with these two diagrams.

00:47:13.930 --> 00:47:17.500
And we identified one
as endothermic and one

00:47:17.500 --> 00:47:19.190
as exothermic.

00:47:19.190 --> 00:47:23.020
So these, again, are our
reaction coordinate diagrams.

00:47:23.020 --> 00:47:24.580
We have PE on one side.

00:47:24.580 --> 00:47:27.050
What does PE stand for again?

00:47:27.050 --> 00:47:29.030
Potential energy.

00:47:29.030 --> 00:47:31.530
It stands for other things too,
but in a reaction coordinate

00:47:31.530 --> 00:47:34.470
diagram, that's what it is.

00:47:34.470 --> 00:47:36.630
And then the reaction
coordinate going this way.

00:47:36.630 --> 00:47:39.840
So we go from reactants to
products along the reaction

00:47:39.840 --> 00:47:41.490
coordinate.

00:47:41.490 --> 00:47:44.430
So here in this
endothermic reaction,

00:47:44.430 --> 00:47:47.210
we have our reactants down
here, our products up here,

00:47:47.210 --> 00:47:50.440
and a very large
activation energy barrier

00:47:50.440 --> 00:47:54.260
for the forward direction, a
much smaller activation energy

00:47:54.260 --> 00:47:56.540
barrier for the
reverse direction.

00:47:56.540 --> 00:47:59.580
With the exothermic
reaction here, we

00:47:59.580 --> 00:48:01.910
have a smaller
activation energy barrier

00:48:01.910 --> 00:48:04.230
for the forward direction
and a bigger one

00:48:04.230 --> 00:48:07.130
for the reverse direction.

00:48:07.130 --> 00:48:09.930
So let's look at the
one equation that

00:48:09.930 --> 00:48:13.170
will be on the exam that will
not be on your equation sheet.

00:48:13.170 --> 00:48:16.000
I think this is--
for this unit, this

00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:20.210
is the one that will be
not on your equation sheet.

00:48:20.210 --> 00:48:24.000
This change in energy is
equal to the activation

00:48:24.000 --> 00:48:25.740
energy for the
forward direction the

00:48:25.740 --> 00:48:28.960
of reaction minus
the activation energy

00:48:28.960 --> 00:48:31.150
for the reverse reaction.

00:48:31.150 --> 00:48:34.080
And again, this is
our delta E here.

00:48:34.080 --> 00:48:35.940
And this is our delta E here.

00:48:35.940 --> 00:48:40.210
Delta E is like delta H. If
you're talking about a gas,

00:48:40.210 --> 00:48:41.920
it's 1% to 2% different.

00:48:41.920 --> 00:48:44.900
If you're talking about
a solid or a liquid,

00:48:44.900 --> 00:48:47.760
it's negligibly different.

00:48:47.760 --> 00:48:52.020
So if we look at this
endothermic reaction here,

00:48:52.020 --> 00:48:54.790
we have a big forward
activation energy

00:48:54.790 --> 00:49:00.270
barrier minus a small reverse
activation energy barrier.

00:49:00.270 --> 00:49:03.600
So that's going to give us a
positive value for delta E.

00:49:03.600 --> 00:49:06.720
And it'll be an
endothermic reaction.

00:49:06.720 --> 00:49:08.880
And if we look at this
equation again and fill it

00:49:08.880 --> 00:49:12.220
in for the exothermic
reaction, we

00:49:12.220 --> 00:49:14.790
have a small barrier in
the forward direction,

00:49:14.790 --> 00:49:17.290
a big barrier in the
reverse direction,

00:49:17.290 --> 00:49:20.190
and a negative value
for delta E and delta H.

00:49:20.190 --> 00:49:23.385
It's an exothermic reaction.

00:49:23.385 --> 00:49:25.010
Now let's think about
what happens when

00:49:25.010 --> 00:49:28.260
we increase the temperature.

00:49:28.260 --> 00:49:31.210
So if we increase
temperature, it's

00:49:31.210 --> 00:49:36.420
a lot easier to overcome this
forward activation energy

00:49:36.420 --> 00:49:38.470
barrier, the big one.

00:49:38.470 --> 00:49:40.990
And that's going to
shift it to products.

00:49:40.990 --> 00:49:43.914
And this is because the small
activation energy barrier,

00:49:43.914 --> 00:49:45.580
it's not that hard
to get over something

00:49:45.580 --> 00:49:47.690
that's a small activation
energy barrier.

00:49:47.690 --> 00:49:48.670
It's not hard.

00:49:48.670 --> 00:49:50.820
But if it's a
really big barrier,

00:49:50.820 --> 00:49:52.740
it's hard to get
over that barrier.

00:49:52.740 --> 00:49:54.580
You need a lot of
kinetic energy.

00:49:54.580 --> 00:49:57.700
Increasing the temperature
will give that kinetic energy

00:49:57.700 --> 00:49:59.180
to overcome that barrier.

00:49:59.180 --> 00:50:01.590
Remember that when
molecules come together,

00:50:01.590 --> 00:50:03.460
bonds are distorted and formed.

00:50:03.460 --> 00:50:05.460
The potential energy
goes up first.

00:50:05.460 --> 00:50:08.120
And only those molecules
with that critical energy

00:50:08.120 --> 00:50:10.710
that can overcome that
activation energy barrier

00:50:10.710 --> 00:50:12.100
can go on to products.

00:50:12.100 --> 00:50:14.410
Increase the temperature,
that allows you

00:50:14.410 --> 00:50:18.210
to overcome the big barrier.

00:50:18.210 --> 00:50:21.407
Now if we look in this side,
this is a small barrier.

00:50:21.407 --> 00:50:22.990
They weren't really
having-- molecules

00:50:22.990 --> 00:50:25.031
were probably not having
a huge amount of trouble

00:50:25.031 --> 00:50:25.890
with that barrier.

00:50:25.890 --> 00:50:29.070
The barrier that was hard was
for the reverse direction.

00:50:29.070 --> 00:50:30.590
So now you increase
the temperature

00:50:30.590 --> 00:50:32.320
of an exothermic reaction.

00:50:32.320 --> 00:50:36.130
It's easier to overcome this big
barrier, the reverse barrier.

00:50:36.130 --> 00:50:38.800
And you have a shift
toward reactants.

00:50:38.800 --> 00:50:40.500
So this is what we
had seen before.

00:50:40.500 --> 00:50:43.380
You increase the temperature
of an endothermic reaction.

00:50:43.380 --> 00:50:45.290
You go to products.

00:50:45.290 --> 00:50:48.780
You increase the temperature
of an exothermic reaction.

00:50:48.780 --> 00:50:50.330
It shifts to reactants.

00:50:50.330 --> 00:50:52.540
So these are the same
things we saw before.

00:50:52.540 --> 00:50:55.380
But now there's a new
rationalization behind it.

00:50:55.380 --> 00:50:58.620
Now we can think about this
in terms of activation energy

00:50:58.620 --> 00:51:00.410
barriers.

00:51:00.410 --> 00:51:03.290
So the important
points to remember,

00:51:03.290 --> 00:51:07.190
big activation energy
barrier, rate constant

00:51:07.190 --> 00:51:10.170
very sensitive to temperature.

00:51:10.170 --> 00:51:14.710
If you have a big barrier,
increasing the temperature

00:51:14.710 --> 00:51:17.120
makes a big difference.

00:51:17.120 --> 00:51:19.820
If you have a small
barrier, doesn't really

00:51:19.820 --> 00:51:21.040
matter that much.

00:51:21.040 --> 00:51:24.280
Most of your molecules can
get over that small barrier.

00:51:24.280 --> 00:51:27.190
So big barrier, increasing
the temperature,

00:51:27.190 --> 00:51:29.000
more molecules can go.

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:31.230
And so you're going to
shift in the direction

00:51:31.230 --> 00:51:33.460
of the big barrier.

